Goodreads Data Analysis

An analysis of the top ten thousand "most frequently rated" books on Goodreads.

By Benjamin Skopets


Goodreads.com was founded in 2006 and by late 2007 had 10 million books registered on its site. This data analysis will be looking at the top ten thousand books on Goodreads, with "top ten thousand" defined by number of reviews on the books. It will also analyze the activity of fifty thousand Goodreads users, each with 20-200 books rated. Books on Goodreads are rated either one, two, three, four, or five stars, with nothing in between. Users may not rate a book as 4.5 stars, for example.


I was motivated to analyze this dataset because I was an avid reader for many years of my life, and still love reading. I loved books such as Sociology/Economics books written by Stephen Dubner, Steven Levitt, and Malcolm Gladwell. I was shocked to learn a few years ago that despite the fact that I thought these books were incredibly well written, provided thought-provoking insights into how life and business works behind the scenes, and were entertaining, they received only 4 star average reviews on Goodreads, instead of the 4.7+ star average reviews I had expected. This made me curious about the psychology of rating books itself, which drew me to this dataset. Hopefully, any readers will be curious about how their favorite books are rated on Goodreads, and overall trends that can be found by analyzing publicly available data about Goodreads book reviews.

First let's look at our main dataset that we will be working with. This dataset contains information about each of the top ten thousand most rated books on Goodreads. It contains each book's title, average rating, the number of 1,2,3,4 and 5-star reviews each book received, its publication date, authors, publication year, and other relevant information.

10000 rows × 23 columns

The first analysis I performed out of curiosity was: was there a significant correlation between year and average average review - yes, "average" should appear there twice - for that year. In other words, did Goodreads users tend to rate older books as better or worse than modern books, or was there no significant relationship to be found?

In [2]:
avgPerYear = b.groupby( 'original_publication_year' ).average_rating.mean()

avgPerYear19thCentury = avgPerYear.iloc[95:171]

avgPerYear19thCentury.plot.line(x = "original_publication_year", y = "average_rating", ylabel = 'Average Average Rating')

avgPerYearSince1900 = avgPerYear.iloc[170:]

avgPerYearSince1900.plot.line(x = "original_publication_year", y = "average_rating", ylabel = 'Average Average Rating')
Out[2]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='original_publication_year', ylabel='Average Average Rating'>

As one can tell, there is very little relationship between the year and average average book rating for that year. The original dataset of books had books going back to 1750 B.C.E., which I felt were outliers that complicated data analysis and interpretation, so I removed them by only keeping books that were published after 1800. This only removed 2% of the books in the original dataset.

Next, I show books published in the year 1813 in our dataset and their average ratings to demonstrate why "spikes" exist in the above graph, i.e years in which the average average book rating was far from the norm of 4.0. What we find is that these years with "spikes" in the graph had very few books published and in our dataset, and their average average rating was far from the norm.

Alphabetical By First Name, Last Name, and Book Title - Analysis


Next, I was curious about whether any relationship existed between the first letter of the author's first name on the one hand and the number of reviews that author's book(s) received and the average review the book(s) received on the other hand. I therefore sorted my dataset alphabetically by first name using Pandas's sort_values function. I then created scatterplots to show these relationships and fitted a regression line to them to see if any significant positive or negative correlation existed between them.


The graphs can be interpreted as follows: the more to the left a datapoint appears, the earlier in the alphabet the first letter of an author's furst name is. The more to the right a datapoint appears, the later in the alphabet the first letter of an author's furst name is.

Results

As one can see, there appears to be no significant relationship between these variables whatsoever. However, I thought that if the top 1,000 most reviewed books are analyzed instead of the top 10,000, perhaps a correlation will appear. The next few graphs demonstrate this once again, using a very similar process as before. I thought a relationship between these variables may appear since it is a known fact that Nobel Prize winners and tenured professors are overrepresented if their last name comes early alphabetically. This is because scientific papers often have their authors listen in alphabetical order, and sometimes only the first author is mentioned, such as Bentley et. al.

More Results

Once again, no significant relationship between these variables was found. This is not necessarily discouraging, as it simply means that for this particular dataset, this particular analysis will never have to be repeated again, as the results are now known, thereby saving Data Scientists' time and satisfying the curiosity of those interested in this topic.

We now turn our attention to a different dataset, this one with roughly six million entries. Each entry represents a user-book combination, where a user with a given user ID from one to 49925 rates a single book from one to five stars. I was curious about the distribution of average ratings across all users in this dataset. That is, if each user had all of their ratings averaged, and then this was plotted for each user, what would the result look like? Pandas's groupby function and a historgram is used to answer this question.

In [26]:

avgRatingPerUser

userInfo['user_ID'] = userInfo.reset_index().index
userInfo.hist(column = "Average Rating For This User", bins = 50)

Making Predictions about Number of 5-Star Reviews

Finally, I made a linear regression model using sklearn to predict - based on the number of 4 star reviews a book had - the number of 5 star reviews it would have. I made a training and testing dataset using a 75%/25% split, and graphed the results of running my linear regression on the testing data set. The results were incredibly good, with the two graphs overlapping except for extremely highly rated books which were outliers.

In [74]:
# Source referenced: https://aegis4048.github.io/mutiple_linear_regression_and_visualization_in_python

from sklearn import model_selection
from sklearn import linear_model
from sklearn import preprocessing
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

x = training_df['ratings_4'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
y = training_df['ratings_5']
 
ols = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model = ols.fit(x, y)

# Using the testing data to generate predictions using the linear model generated from the trainin dataset.
x_pred = testing_df['ratings_4']    
x_pred = x_pred.values.reshape(-1, 1)
y_pred = model.predict(x_pred)

plt.style.use('default')
plt.style.use('ggplot')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 3.5))

ax.plot(x_pred, y_pred, color='b', label='Regression model')
ax.scatter(x, y, edgecolor='k', facecolor='red', alpha=0.7, label='Sample data')
ax.set_ylabel('5-Star Ratings', fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel('4-Star Ratings', fontsize=14)
ax.legend(facecolor='white', fontsize=11)
ax.text(0.55, 0.15, '$y = %.2f x_1 - %.2f $' % (model.coef_[0], abs(model.intercept_)), fontsize=17, transform=ax.transAxes)

fig.tight_layout()
